Evidence suggests that young women in Maldives feel a need for better contraception information, education, and service access, most especially in rural areas. This is important as views of young men regarding the provision of free contraceptive methods such as condoms and educational materials, emphasis on fertility awareness, and recommendations to practice safer sex are also prominent.

In Somalia, 89% of women and girls of child bearing age use any modern contraceptive method to space children and limit unwanted pregnancy. Twenty two percent of married women in the country’s capital, Mogadishu, use some form of modern contraceptives to space children. In six out of ten marriages, the husband –1 who is around 12 years older than his wife- is the sole arbiter of family size and contraceptive use, a more favorable position of reproductive autonomy than is found in other African countries. Furthermore, Somali women increasingly voice privacy and confidentiality concerns and cite that they are concerned about outside family members interfering and learning that they use contraceptives. Confidentiality is also a relationship issue, with husbands and in-laws often prying into intimate payment issues, creating a barrier among Somali women and healthcare providers.

By Lina Henry
